title: For Sale:  Yes, you can get ammo cheap!
postcontent:
In the past 5 days at Walmart I have seen and purchased:
100 rd pack Federal Champion .45ACP - $32.17
100 rd pack WWB 9mm - $24.47
50 rd Tula .45 - $14.95
50 rd Tula .380 - $14.95

Just missed 100 rd 9mm Federal Champion at $21 and change, and a friend bought 100 rd Federal .223 for somewhere around $32.  

.22LR prices there are virtually unchanged for the most part though none was in stock.

All of this ammo sat on the shelves for up to 2 days and more.  This was in multiple shipments, not all there at once.  You don't have to skip work to find ammo, it's put out throughout the day and evening.  Your LGS has ammo too.  If it's reasonably priced, then support them.  If it's not, let them know.

To the person wanting to start the Google group:  I have a feeling that will become moocher city.  There are too many that want to hoard or make a profit off of it.  I salute your idea though.

Boycott SGAmmo (respected but sell Win and Rem 525 bulk for $40+), Target Sports USA (selling Rem bucket o bullets for $160), Cheaper Than Uranium (gouging everything), LuckyGunner (selling 1000 rd S&B 9mm FMJ for $789), Ammunition Depot

The longer you pay inflated prices, the longer they'll stay that way.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Interarms (Rossi) 92 Puma 38 Spcl / 357 Mag 16" Carbine (Trapper)
postcontent: TEMPORARY PRICE DROP: I'm dropping the price temporarily in order to liquidate quickly to purchase other weapons on my wish list. I have for sale/trade a Rare late 80s / early 90s Interarms (Rossi) 92 Puma Carbine / Trapper with a 16.25" barrel chambered in 38 Special / 357 Mag. This was well before Braztech--and far superior! This rifle was made by Rossi (barrel with "Amadaeo Rossi" stamp) for the USA market imported by Interarms. This is a very fine specimen of the rare model with the Puma on the left side of the receiver. This rifle has seen VERY little use and maybe unfired. This is a saddle ring model but as you can see from the photos a previous owner removed the ring to avoid scratching the receiver and to keep it from rattling. The saddle rings are available very cheaply if you want to replace it. If you know Rossi 92 lever guns the actions are very, very stiff out of the box and need the action worked over and over again and/or shot a lot to loosen up at which point they are some of the finest versions of the famous Winchester model 1892 lever action rifle. This action was VERY stiff when I got it. I have worked it some and have gotten it somewhat loosenend up but still needs more. This stiffness, the bore being spotless and the gun having virtually no wear except for the action working I did lead me to believe this gun is in near new condition, maybe unfired. but I'm selling as "used". I have not shot the gun. The wood and metal are gorgeous. I am refining my collection to Winchester lever actions and maybe a few Marlin so I'm going to let this go. I will sell outright or will trade:
